Here are 10 time management tips that I genuinely use day-to-day ğŸ§µ
1 - We own all of our time

We can easily slip into this weird relationship with time, where we feel like weâ€™re racing against the clock to get things done. Realising that we own our own time is a powerful shift.
Instead of saying â€˜I donâ€™t have timeâ€™, say â€˜Iâ€™m choosing to do this task now, and that task laterâ€™. It gives you back control over what you spend time on and can help you prioritise better.

https://t.co/N72EsvjQnw
2 - Hell yeah or no

A very simple mental model coined by Derek @sivers to help you make better decisions.

When weâ€™re young, thereâ€™s more value in saying yes to pretty much every opportunity that comes our way.
@sivers But as we progress in life and in our careers, we start getting more opportunities and itâ€™s impossible to say yes to them all.

The way to counter that is to make decisions by saying either â€˜hell yeahâ€™ or â€˜hell noâ€™. If itâ€™s not a â€˜hell yeahâ€™ straight away, we should let it pass.
@sivers 3 - The daily highlight

This is straight from my favourite productivity book â€˜Make Timeâ€™ by John Zeratsky @jazer

The idea is that each day, weÂ choose one specific task that we want to get done, simply saving us from an overly long to-do list and analysis paralysis.
@sivers @jazer 4 - Use a to-do list

Thereâ€™s so much going on in our brain every day, thereâ€™s no way we can store a perfect list of everything we need to do.

Do yourself a favour and keep a daily checklist of tasks so you can stay on track.
@sivers @jazer Having a physical to-do list in front of your eyes is a really pleasant experience and youâ€™re less likely to switch away from an app and never check it again.

If youâ€™re looking for a new to-do list or planner, mine are currently 50% off: https://t.co/db4AiyWV40
@sivers @jazer 5 - Time blocking

Whenever we have a task to do we should put a time block in our calendar just for this thing - it really is as simple as it sounds

I like to use this technique in combination with the daily highlight to make sure the most important task is protected in my cal.
@sivers @jazer 6 - Parkinsonâ€™s Law

Parkinsonâ€™s Law states that work expands to fill the time we allocate to it.
@elonmusk setâ€™s himself incredibly short deadlines so, even if he doesnâ€™t finish the whole task, heâ€™s gotten ahead with some progress.
@sivers @jazer @elonmusk To take advantage of Parkinsonâ€™s Law we need to leverage deadlines, even if theyâ€™re somewhat artificial. Putting pressure on when you need to get a task done by will help you tick it off.
@sivers @jazer @elonmusk If you want to learn more about the laws of productivity, I have a Skillshare class on it here: https://t.co/ZwzCS4jB4t
@sivers @jazer @elonmusk 7 - Protected time

If you don't protect your time, your day can easily get filled up with meetings. Schedule a block of your day for protected task time.

These days I set my protected time for the first 4 hours of my mornings and I use it to write my book.
@sivers @jazer @elonmusk 8 - Delegation

When most people hear about delegation their instant response is â€œI donâ€™t have enough money.â€ And I get it. Itâ€™s a valid concern.

The way I got over that doubt was by setting a fixed hourly rate. A dollar value of my time.
@sivers @jazer @elonmusk Back when I was starting my first business, I decided that an hour of my time would be worth $20.

If something could be delegated for cheaper, Iâ€™d use services likeÂ Fiverr to hire freelancers who were more than happy to do things like data entry or video editing.
@sivers @jazer @elonmusk 9 - Automated scheduling

With different time zones and calendars, scheduling a single meeting can take up to 20 minutes.

At some point, this became too much trouble so I decided to try out some kind of scheduling software - I settled on the Calendly and have never looked back.
@sivers @jazer @elonmusk 10 - The choice to be satisfied

The last tip is more philosophical. For us productivity nerds,Â itâ€™s easy to feel dissatisfied at the end of the day.

We can either stress out about the things we havenâ€™t managed to do or choose to be satisfied with the work weâ€™ve done.
@sivers @jazer @elonmusk Choosing to be satisfied will likely have a more positive impact on our behaviour and performance the next day.

If youâ€™re interested in this topic and want to hear more, I have a video on how I manage my time: https://t.co/OcD0HGOjRM

